ce:caption.ce:simple-para:
Timeline summarizing key developments in the synthesis and functional evolution of carbon quantum dots (CQDs) over the past two decades. The journey began in 2004 with the first report of fluorescent CQDs (Xu et al.), followed by significant advancements such as enhanced fluorescence (Sun et al., 2006), the emergence of multicolor-emitting and functionalized variants (Liu et al., 2007; 
                     Bourlinos et al., 2008; 
                     Liu et al., 2009), and the development of water-soluble CQDs suitable for biosensing and protein detection (Li et al., 2010; Xu et al., 2012). Between 2015 and 2020 (Liu et al., 2015; Yuan et al., 2017; Guo et al., 2020), research focused on tunable emission properties, CQDs-based nanosensors, and environmentally friendly synthesis methods, including nitrogen doping and microwave-assisted techniques. More recent progress (Nguyen et al., 2022; Dipcin et al., 2024) highlights scalable and cost-effective production strategies, such as continuous-flow hydrothermal synthesis. Looking ahead, the field is rapidly expanding toward multifunctional applications. Future directions include the integration of CQDs into precision agriculture (e.g., nanofertilizers and soil sensors), biomedical applications such as bioimaging, drug delivery, and diagnostics, and environmental monitoring—positioning CQDs as versatile nanomaterials at the intersection of sustainability, technology, and human health.

ce:section.ce:para:
The observed fluorescence emission wavelength is highly dependent on multiple synthetic factors, including the type of carbon precursor, reaction temperature and time, solvent polarity, and dopant concentration. Even small changes in these parameters can lead to substantial shifts in emission spectra, allowing for precise tuning from blue to red emissions. For example, higher reaction temperatures typically enhance graphitization and promote red-shifted emission due to the formation of larger sp² domains, while lower temperatures favor defect-related emission at shorter wavelengths (Wang and Hu, 2014; 
                        Behboudi et al., 2019; 
                        Li et al., 2022). These tunable optical characteristics make CQDs highly adaptable for diverse photonic and sensing applications.
